3 things that matter to me right now and forever:

✌🏽It’s not so much about “finding” peace as it is recognizing and accepting those moments when it has arrived. Internalizing everything that happens to you is natural but energetically wasteful. When things come at you sideways try to remember it isn’t about you. Only accept the tasks that are yours. Not your restaurant server’s anger, your friend’s projection onto you , or the life someone else showcases on social media. You don’t need to attend that thing no matter how strong the pressure. Your value, worth and belonging don’t come from outside of yourself. 

🪩 Be you, unapologetically. Probably the toughest thing to get comfortable with — authenticity and self-acceptance. Loving yourself for who you are in this moment. It dramatically lowers the burden of everyday life when you’re living for yourself and not others. Presence becomes commonplace — yesterday and tomorrow get pushed more towards the margins. Added bonus, it’s our greatest filter towards identifying what can stay and what should go — from people to behavior patterns. It’s a state of comfort few know. Try saying “I love you” to yourself in the mirror — it ain’t easy.

🌱 Growth and failure are often synonymous. The best thing you can do when facing fear or challenge is to just walk into it head on. We don’t get positive change by promising ourselves movement in the future. We often sit longer in the things that ail us. Both directions are scary as hell. You don’t need to place expectations on yourself. It’s not the outcome, it’s the action. See above about acceptance — you’re not going to be great or even good at everything you try. Ask yourself why that even matters… Growth and failure are often synonymous; success is arbitrary and often societally defined. Choose a different measuring stick for purpose and well-being.

Weight has been a tumultuous thing for me throughout my adult life, and something I’ve never wanted to ‘name.’ As an avoidant, often I keep myself from naming things because then it would require attention.

Recently, I did a drama in therapy that was based on a feeling I experienced at a wedding over the weekend. Some new friends were snapping a photo of the group. When I peeped the preview on the iPhone, I instantly felt mortified. I was wearing a turtleneck — all black attire. I could hear one of my bullies from middle school calling me “Big head!”

When I weighed over 225lbs, the voices were worse. “Big head! Fat head!” That same shame and ridicule was felt through the body as I saw my stomach at the beach or when I caught a glimpse of myself in the mirror.

In the drama, I asked several questions to my collaborators — “Do I look good?” “Do you think I’m smart?” “Do you think I do good work?” “Do you think people like me?” I expected to be triggered by the first question but the last was the one responsible for the tears. It’s all related isn’t it?

Since the shame came externally; I looked to resolve it externally. It’s taken 20 years to confront my reality, and realize the resolution was inside this entire time. I love you dude.
________
